# TypeScript Category with Nested SubCategories Issue

It sounds like you have a type mismatch where your function returns an array of categories, but the data actually includes nested subcategories that aren't properly represented in your type definition.

## Solution Approaches

There are a few ways to solve this:

### 1. Update the Category Type Definition

Define your Category type to include the subcategory relationship:

```typescript
interface SubCategory {
  id: number;
  name: string;
  // other subcategory properties
}

interface Category {
  id: number;
  name: string;
  // other category properties
  subCategories: SubCategory[]; // Add this to represent the nested data
}
```

### 2. Transform the SQL Data

If your SQL query returns a flattened result with repeated category data for each subcategory, you'll need to transform it:

```typescript
function transformRawDataToCategoriesWithSubcategories(rows: any[]): Category[] {
  const categoriesMap = new Map<number, Category>();

  rows.forEach(row => {
    // If this category hasn't been processed yet
    if (!categoriesMap.has(row.category_id)) {
      categoriesMap.set(row.category_id, {
        id: row.category_id,
        name: row.category_name,
        // other category properties
        subCategories: []
      });
    }

    // Add the subcategory to the appropriate category
    if (row.subcategory_id) {
      const category = categoriesMap.get(row.category_id);
      category.subCategories.push({
        id: row.subcategory_id,
        name: row.subcategory_name,
        // other subcategory properties
      });
    }
  });

  return Array.from(categoriesMap.values());
}
```

### 3. Use a More Specific Return Type

If your function is actually returning a more complex structure than just Category[], update the return type to reflect this:

```typescript
function getCategories(): Array<Category & { subCategories: SubCategory[] }> {
  // Your implementation
}
```

